      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors earlier. They were unintentional, but I will do my best to provide clear, straightforward construction advice without the unnecessary comparisons.\n\nTo determine if a wall is load-bearing, you can follow these actual steps:\n\n1.  **Check the Location:** Load-bearing walls are typically located along the exterior perimeter of the house or in the center of the floor plan (between the center of the floor joists). Interior walls that run parallel to the exterior walls are often load-bearing, while walls that run perpendicular to the exterior walls are usually non-load-bearing partitions.\n2.  **Inspect the Ceiling:** Look up at the ceiling directly above the wall. If you see a beam or a joist running directly above the wall, it is almost certainly load-bearing. If the wall is just between joists without a beam above it, it is likely a partition.\n3.  **Check the Foundation:** If you can see the foundation or basement walls, load-bearing walls will often sit directly on top of the foundation or have a concrete beam (header) above them. Partition walls usually do not have this structural support.\n4.  **Consult Blueprints:** The",
